CA - Introduction To SDLC & Need For Version Control & Build Tools
Introduction to DevOps & the Need for Build Tools
1. Understanding the Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC)
Before diving into build tools like Maven and Gradle, it's essential to understand how software has traditionally been
developed. The Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC) provides a structured approach to building software
efficiently.
One of the earliest models of SDLC is the Waterfall Model, which follows a linear and sequential process where each
phase must be fully completed before moving to the next. However, this model has several limitations, which led to the
adoption of Agile and DevOps methodologies.
2. Waterfall Model: A Step-by-Step Approach
The Waterfall Model consists of six distinct phases:
ó¾ ® Requirement Analysis
ğŸ“Œ The first interaction always happens between the Business Analyst (BA) and the Client. ğŸ“Œ The BA prepares the CRS (Client Requirement Specification) before even preparing the SRS (Software
Requirement Specification). ğŸ“Œ The final SRS document defines all system functionalities before development begins.
ó¾ ¯ Design
ğŸ“Œ The architecture of the software is planned based on the requirements.
ğŸ“Œ High-Level Design (HLD) and Low-Level Design (LLD) are created.
ğŸ“Œ Technologies, frameworks, and databases are chosen.
ó¾ ° Coding (Implementation)
ğŸ“Œ Developers write the code based on the design.
ğŸ“Œ Code is divided into modules and integrated later. ğŸ“Œ Best practices like version control (e.g., Git) are followed.
ó¾ ± Testing
ğŸ“Œ Testers verify if the software meets the SRS specifications. ğŸ“Œ Types of testing include unit testing, integration testing, and system testing. ğŸ“Œ Bugs are reported to developers for fixing.
ó¾ ² Deployment
ğŸ“Œ The software is released to production.
ğŸ“Œ Deployment can be on-premises or cloud-based. ğŸ“Œ The software becomes available for real-world users.
12
Coders Arcade â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â” DevOps Lab Manual
Â© 2025 Coders Arcade ğŸ“º www.youtube.com/c/codersarcade ğŸ‘¤ Saurav Sarkar
ó¾ ³ Maintenance
ğŸ“Œ Post-deployment, updates, bug fixes, and improvements are continuously made.
ğŸ“Œ Performance monitoring and security patches are applied.
3. Waterfall Model - Block-Based Diagram
4. Problems with the Waterfall Model
ğŸš© Rigid & Inflexible â€“ Changes cannot be made once a phase is completed.
ğŸš© Late Bug Detection â€“ Testing happens after coding, making bug fixes costly. ğŸš© Slow Development Process â€“ Each phase must be completed before the next starts.
ğŸš© Not Suitable for Modern Agile Environments â€“ Does not support rapid iteration.
5. Introduction to Agile Methodology
To overcome Waterfall's limitations, the Agile Model was introduced. Agile promotes iterative and incremental
development, allowing teams to deliver software faster with continuous feedback.
Key Agile Concepts
âœ… Sprints â€“ Development happens in short cycles, usually lasting 7-14 days. âœ… Scrum Master â€“ Facilitates Agile processes and removes blockers for the team.
âœ… Daily Stand-up Meetings â€“ Short meetings where team members discuss:
ó¾ ® What they did yesterday?
ó¾ ¯ What they plan to do today?
ó¾ ° Any blockers?
âœ… Retrospective Meetings â€“ At the end of each sprint, the team reflects on what worked well and what can be
improved.
Sprint Retrospective: The 4Ls Framework
The 4Ls retrospective is a common technique used in tech interviews:
1 â”Œâ”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”
2 â”‚ ó¾ ® Requirement Analysis â”‚
3 â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â–¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜
4 â”Œâ”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”
5 â”‚ ó¾ ¯ Design â”‚
6 â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â–¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜
7 â”Œâ”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”
8 â”‚ ó¾ ° Coding â”‚
9 â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â–¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜
10 â”Œâ”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”
11 â”‚ ó¾ ± Testing â”‚
12 â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â–¼â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜
