ğŸ”¹ Loved â€“ What went well in the sprint?
ğŸ”¹ Longed for â€“ What do we wish had happened?
ğŸ”¹ Loathed â€“ What went wrong or was frustrating?
ğŸ”¹ Learned â€“ What new knowledge or skills were gained?
6. The Transition from Agile to DevOps
While Agile improved development, deployment and operations remained slow. This led to the birth of DevOps,
which introduced:
ğŸ”¹ Continuous Integration & Deployment (CI/CD)
ğŸ”¹ Automation of Builds, Testing, and Deployment
ğŸ”¹ Faster & More Reliable Software Releases
To make DevOps efficient, we need Build Tools like Maven & Gradle, which simplify project management.
7. The Clumsy Manual Approach to Project Setup
Before introducing Maven & Gradle, letâ€™s look at how we manually created a Selenium Automation Test Project.
Manual Setup Process
ó¾ ® Created a Simple Java Project in IntelliJ IDEA (Selenium Automation Test).
ó¾ ¯ Manually Downloaded the Selenium JAR from:
ğŸ”— https://www.selenium.dev
ó¾ ° Created a lib folder and placed selenium-server-4.28.1.jar inside it.
ó¾ ± Manually Added the Dependency in IntelliJ IDEA:
File â†’ Project Structure â†’ Libraries â†’ Add Selenium JAR â†’ Apply â†’ OK
ó¾ ² Wrote a Selenium Test in Java ( LoginTest.java ) to validate login at https://www.saucedemo.com. ó¾ ³ Ran the test manually in IntelliJ IDEA.
Java Selenium Code for Login Automation
1 import org.openqa.selenium.By;
2 import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
3 import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
4
5 public class LoginTest {
6 public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
7 WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
8 driver.get("https://www.saucedemo.com/");
9 driver.manage().window().maximize();
10 Thread.sleep(2000);
11 driver.findElement(By.id("user-name")).sendKeys("standard_user");
12 Thread.sleep(2000);
13 driver.findElement(By.id("password")).sendKeys("secret_sauce");
14 Thread.sleep(2000);
15 driver.findElement(By.id("login-button")).click();
16 Thread.sleep(2000);
17 driver.quit();
18 }
19 }
