Coders Arcade â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â” DevOps Lab Manual
Â© 2025 Coders Arcade ğŸ“º www.youtube.com/c/codersarcade ğŸ‘¤ Saurav Sarkar
Maven's Three Built-in Lifecycles
1. Clean Lifecycle â€“ Cleans the project.
2. Default (Build) Lifecycle â€“ Handles project compilation, testing, packaging, and deployment.
3. Site Lifecycle â€“ Generates project documentation.
Each lifecycle has a sequence of phases, which execute in order.
1. Clean Lifecycle
Used to remove old build files before a new build.
Phases:
pre-clean â†’ Executes tasks before cleaning.
clean â†’ Deletes the /target directory (removes compiled files).
post-clean â†’ Executes tasks after cleaning.
Command to Run:
(This removes all compiled files and resets the build environment.)
2. Default (Build) Lifecycle
This is the main lifecycle that compiles, tests, and packages the project.
Phases & Explanation:
1. validate â†’ Ensures project structure and configuration are correct.
2. compile â†’ Compiles the source code.
3. test â†’ Runs unit tests using JUnit/TestNG (does not require deployment).
4. package â†’ Packages the compiled code into a deployable format (e.g., JAR/WAR).
5. verify â†’ Runs integration tests to check if the package is valid.
6. install â†’ Installs the package into the local repository ( ~/.m2/repository ).
7. deploy â†’ Uploads the package to a remote repository (e.g., Nexus, Artifactory).
Commands to Run Each Phase:
Note: Running mvn package will also execute validate, compile, and test (because earlier phases are executed
automatically).
1 mvn clean
2
1 mvn validate # Check project structure
2 mvn compile # Compile the source code
3 mvn test # Run unit tests
4 mvn package # Create JAR/WAR file
5 mvn verify # Run integration tests
6 mvn install # Install JAR to local repository
7 mvn deploy # Deploy to remote repository
8
