ğŸ’¡ Pros & Cons of Using Gradle
âœ… Pros
âœ” Declarative Builds â€“ Uses Groovy/Kotlin DSL for configuration.
âœ” Highly Scalable â€“ Efficient for both small and large projects.
âœ” Performance Boost â€“ Incremental builds and parallel execution speed up the process.
âœ” Cross-Language Support â€“ Works with Java, Groovy, Kotlin, Scala, C++, etc.
âœ” Strong Dependency Management â€“ Handles dependencies efficiently.
âœ” Free & Open Source â€“ Available under Apache License 2.0.
âŒ Cons
â— Requires Technical Knowledge â€“ Needs prior understanding of Groovy/Kotlin DSL. â— Complex Configurations â€“ Initial setup can be tricky for beginners.
â— Resource Consumption â€“ Uses more memory compared to Maven. â— Migration Difficulty â€“ Moving from Maven/Ant to Gradle requires effort.
ğŸ“š Conclusion
Gradle is a powerful, flexible, and efficient build automation tool. It has become a developer-favorite for projects of
all sizes, from small applications to large enterprise systems. With incremental builds, dependency
management, and extensive plugin support, Gradle makes software development faster and smoother. ğŸš€
